### ─── Variables ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
@keycloak     = http://localhost:8180
@gateway      = http://localhost:8081
@service      = http://localhost:8080
@service2     = http://localhost:8082
@realm        = example-service-realm
@clientId     = example-service-client
@clientSecret = example-service-secret

### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### 1. PUBLIC ENDPOINTS — No authentication required
### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### 1a. Public hello (direct to service)
GET {{service}}/api/public/hello

###

### 1b. Service info (direct to service)
GET {{service}}/api/public/info

###

### 1c. Public hello via API Gateway
GET {{gateway}}/api/public/hello

###

### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### 2. AUTHENTICATION — Get tokens from Keycloak
### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### 2a. Get user token from example-service-realm
# @name loginResponse
POST {{keycloak}}/realms/{{realm}}/protocol/openid-connect/token
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

username=testuser&password=testpass&grant_type=password&client_id={{clientId}}&client_secret={{clientSecret}}

###

### 2b. Decode the token (paste your token here)
# @name decodeToken
# Tip: Use https://jwt.io to inspect the claims, especially:
#   - "iss" (issuer) → should be http://localhost:8180/realms/example-service-realm
#   - "preferred_username" → testuser

### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### 3. DIRECT SERVICE ACCESS — Token from example-service-realm
### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# The example-service accepts tokens directly from example-service-realm.
# Copy the access_token from step 2a and paste below.

@exampleToken = PASTE_ACCESS_TOKEN_HERE

### 3a. Protected hello (direct to service, original realm token)
GET {{service}}/api/protected/hello
Authorization: Bearer {{exampleToken}}

###

### 3b. Token introspection (see which realm issued the token)
GET {{service}}/api/protected/token-info
Authorization: Bearer {{exampleToken}}

###

### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### 4. VIA API GATEWAY — Token Exchange in action
### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# When you send the example-service-realm token through the Gateway:
#   1. Gateway intercepts the request
#   2. Gateway calls Keycloak to exchange the token → gateway-realm token
#   3. Gateway forwards the request with the NEW token
#   4. example-service receives and validates the gateway-realm token
#
# The response from /api/protected/token-info will show:
#   "issuer": "http://localhost:8180/realms/gateway-realm"  ← exchanged!

### 4a. Protected hello via Gateway (token exchange happens transparently)
GET {{gateway}}/api/protected/hello
Authorization: Bearer {{exampleToken}}

###

### 4b. Token info via Gateway (shows the EXCHANGED gateway-realm token)
GET {{gateway}}/api/protected/token-info
Authorization: Bearer {{exampleToken}}

###

### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### 5. MANUAL TOKEN EXCHANGE — See the exchange yourself
### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# You can also perform the token exchange manually to see exactly what happens.

### 5a. Exchange example-service-realm token → gateway-realm token
POST {{keycloak}}/realms/gateway-realm/protocol/openid-connect/token
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

grant_type=urn:ietf:params:oauth:grant-type:token-exchange&subject_token={{exampleToken}}&subject_token_type=urn:ietf:params:oauth:token-type:access_token&requested_token_type=urn:ietf:params:oauth:token-type:access_token&client_id=gateway-client&client_secret=gateway-client-secret

###

### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### 6. INFRASTRUCTURE HEALTH CHECKS
### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### 6a. Keycloak health
GET {{keycloak}}/health/ready

###

### 6b. Eureka dashboard
GET http://localhost:8761

###

### 6c. API Gateway health
GET {{gateway}}/actuator/health

###

### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### 7. CHAINED FLOW — Full round-trip: Client → Gateway → Service → Service2
### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# This demonstrates the complete token exchange chain:
#
#   ① Client sends example-service-realm token to Gateway
#   ② Gateway exchanges it → gateway-realm token
#   ③ Gateway forwards to example-service (with gateway-realm token)
#   ④ example-service calls example-service2 (same gateway-realm token forwarded)
#   ⑤ example-service2 validates the gateway-realm token and responds
#   ⑥ example-service assembles a combined response and returns to client
#
# The /api/protected/chained endpoint makes this hop chain visible.
# You will see three integration steps in the response:
#   "gatewayStep"  → info from token exchange at gateway
#   "service1Step" → token info seen by example-service
#   "service2Step" → token info seen by example-service2
#
# Note: Use the same testuser token as in step 3. The exchange is automatic.

### 7a. Chained call via Gateway (full round-trip)
# Expected: response with 3 steps; all showing gateway-realm as issuer
GET {{gateway}}/api/protected/chained
Authorization: Bearer {{exampleToken}}

###

### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### 8. DIRECT ACCESS TO example-service2 VIA GATEWAY
### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# The Gateway also exposes a direct route to example-service2 under /api/service2/.
# The token exchange filter is applied here too — so clients still send
# their example-service-realm token and the gateway exchanges it automatically.
#
# Path rewrite: /api/service2/internal/hello → /api/internal/hello (StripPrefix)

### 8a. Public info from service2 via Gateway (no auth required)
GET {{gateway}}/api/service2/public/info

###

### 8b. Internal hello from service2 via Gateway (token exchange applied)
GET {{gateway}}/api/service2/internal/hello
Authorization: Bearer {{exampleToken}}

###

### 8c. Full token claims from service2 via Gateway
GET {{gateway}}/api/service2/internal/token-info
Authorization: Bearer {{exampleToken}}

###

### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### 9. DIRECT ACCESS TO example-service2 (NO GATEWAY — shows auth enforcement)
### ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# example-service2 listens on port 8082 but in a real deployment it would
# not be publicly exposed (only internal Docker network access).
#
# These calls show what happens when you try to bypass the gateway:

### 9a. Public info (no token required — works fine)
GET {{service2}}/api/public/info

###

### 9b. Internal endpoint with ORIGINAL token (example-service-realm) — FAILS (401)
# example-service2 only trusts gateway-realm tokens.
# Sending an example-service-realm token directly should return 401.
GET {{service2}}/api/internal/hello
Authorization: Bearer {{exampleToken}}

###

### 9c. Internal endpoint with EXCHANGED token — WORKS
# After manual exchange (step 5a), paste the exchanged gateway-realm token here.
@gatewayToken = PASTE_EXCHANGED_GATEWAY_TOKEN_HERE
GET {{service2}}/api/internal/hello
Authorization: Bearer {{gatewayToken}}

###

###

### 6d. Example Service health
GET {{service}}/actuator/health

###

### 6e. Example Service Swagger UI
GET {{service}}/swagger-ui.html

###

### 6f. API Gateway routes info
GET {{gateway}}/actuator/gateway/routes

###
